2 A separate model for each sex group

2.1 A general statistical model

The observation \(y_{it}\) for subject \(i\) at time \(t\):

\[\begin{equation*} y_{it} = f(t) + r_i(t) + e_{it}, \end{equation*}\]

  • \(f(t)\), the population trajectory;

  • \(r_i(t)\), the deviation of subject \(i\)s trajectory from \(f(t)\).

2.2 Model specification in mgcv

The population trajectory \(f(t)\) is specified as:

s(t, bs = "ps", k = ?, m = c(2, 2))

  • t, the name (to be substituted) of the time variable.

  • bs, type of spline basis; ps for P-splines.

  • k, the number of basis functions used to express each random curve; for ps, it is the number of B-splines.

  • m, penalty information. c(2, 2) for cubic B-splines penalized by 2nd order differences.

The subject-specific deviation trajectory \(r_i(t)\) is specified as:

s(t, i, bs = "fs", xt = "ps", k = ?, m = c(2, 1))

  • t, the name (to be substituted) of the time variable.

  • i, the name (to be substituted) of the subject ID variable; must be provided as a factor .

  • "fs", the proper way for setting up random curves.

  • xt (short for extra), used to specify the spline basis for each random curve.

  • k, the number of basis functions used to express each random curve; for ps, it is the number of B-splines.

  • m, penalty information. c(2, 1) for cubic B-splines penalized by 1nd order differences.

2.3 Model fitting in mgcv

In this context, the mgcv model formula is:

form <- bmi ~ s(lage, bs = 'ps', k = 10, m = c(2, 2)) +
  s(lage, id, bs = "fs", xt = "ps", k = 10, m = c(2, 1))

We fit this model using mgcv::gamm() or gamm4::gamm4(), not mgcv::gam() or mgcv::bam().

fit <- gamm(form, data = mbmi100)
## Warning in gam.side(sm, X, tol = .Machine$double.eps^0.5): model has repeated 1-
## d smooths of same variable.

2.4 Covariate grids

For prediction purpose.

age.grid <- seq(min(mbmi100$age), max(mbmi100$age), length.out = 100)
id.grid <- factor(levels(mbmi100$id), levels(mbmi100$id))

2.5 Predict and plot all subject trajectories

Easy to do; just use predict to predict the response variable.

## a data.frame
subtraj <- expand.grid(age = age.grid, id = id.grid)
subtraj$lage <- log(age.grid)
## add predicted values to data.frame
subtraj$bmi <- predict(fit$gam, newdata = subtraj)
## plot
ggplot(data = subtraj, mapping = aes(age, bmi)) + 
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = id), show.legend = FALSE)

2.6 Plot trajectories for a few subjects

## example subjects (you can choose your own)
id.selected <- levels(mbmi100$id)[seq(1, nlevels(mbmi100$id), length.out = 6)]
## subset data.frames
mbmi100.selected <- subset(mbmi100, id %in% id.selected)
subtraj.selected <- subset(subtraj, id %in% id.selected)
## plot
ggplot(data = subtraj.selected, mapping = aes(age, bmi)) + 
  geom_line(data = subtraj.selected, mapping = aes(color = id), show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(facets = vars(id)) +
  geom_point(data = mbmi100.selected, mapping = aes(color = id), show.legend = FALSE)

2.7 Predict and plot population trajectory

This is harder, as you need to know more about mgcvs smooth construction.

## a data.frame
poptraj <- data.frame(age = age.grid, lage = log(age.grid))

## use gratia to process a single smooth function/term
spl.term <- get_smooth(fit$gam, "s(lage)")
spl.value <- eval_smooth(spl.term, model = fit$gam, data = poptraj)$data[[1]]$est

## add predicted values to data.frame
poptraj$bmi <- spl.value + fit$gam$coefficients[["(Intercept)"]]
ggplot(data = poptraj, mapping = aes(age, bmi)) + geom_line()

3 A joint model for both sex groups

head(bmi100 <- getBMI100("A"))
##          age       lage      bmi   id sex
## 1 0.09329162 -2.3720250 13.58572 M001   M
## 2 0.17268363 -1.7562941 15.38245 M001   M
## 3 0.24609857 -1.4020231 15.33981 M001   M
## 4 0.34023873 -1.0781078 16.20743 M001   M
## 5 0.40999551 -0.8916091 15.90694 M001   M
## 6 0.50694408 -0.6793546 16.95482 M001   M

3.1 A general statistical model

The observation \(y_{it}\) for subject \(i\) (belong to group \(j\)) at time \(t\):

\[\begin{equation*} y_{it} = f_j(t) + r_i(t) + e_{it}, \end{equation*}\]

  • \(f_j(t)\), the population trajectory for group \(j\);

  • \(r_i(t)\), the deviation of subject \(i\)s trajectory from \(f(t)\).

3.2 Model specification in mgcv

The population trajectory \(f_j(t)\) is specifed as:

j + s(t, by = j, bs = "ps", k = ?, m = c(2, 2))

  • j, the name (to be substituted) of the population group variable; must be provided as a factor .

  • t, the name (to be substituted) of the time variable.

  • bs, type of spline basis; ps for P-splines.

  • k, the number of basis functions used to express each random curve; for ps, it is the number of B-splines.

  • m, penalty information. c(2, 2) for cubic B-splines penalized by 2nd order differences.

The subject-specific deviation trajectory \(r_i(t)\) is specified as:

s(t, i, bs = "fs", xt = "ps", k = ?, m = c(2, 1))

  • t, the name (to be substituted) of the time variable.

  • i, the name (to be substituted) of the subject ID variable; must be provided as a factor .

  • "fs", the proper way for setting up random curves.

  • xt (short for extra), used to specify the spline basis for each random curve.

  • k, the number of basis functions used to express each random curve; for ps, it is the number of B-splines.

  • m, penalty information. c(2, 1) for cubic B-splines penalized by 1nd order differences.

3.3 Model fitting in mgcv

In this context, the mgcv model formula is:

form <- bmi ~ sex + s(lage, by = sex, bs = 'ps', k = 10, m = c(2, 2)) +
  s(lage, id, bs = "fs", xt = "ps", k = 10, m = c(2, 1))

We fit this model using mgcv::gamm() or gamm4::gamm4(), not mgcv::gam() or mgcv::bam().

fit <- gamm(form, data = bmi100)

3.4 Covariate grids

For prediction purpose.

age.grid <- seq(min(bmi100$age), max(bmi100$age), length.out = 100)
id.grid <- factor(levels(bmi100$id), levels(bmi100$id))
sex.grid <- factor(levels(bmi100$sex), levels(bmi100$sex))

3.5 Predict and plot all aubject trajectories

subtraj <- expand.grid(age = age.grid, id = id.grid)
subtraj$sex <- substr(subtraj$id, 1, 1)  ##?
subtraj$lage <- log(age.grid)

subtraj$bmi <- predict(fit$gam, newdata = subtraj)
ggplot(data = subtraj, mapping = aes(age, bmi)) + 
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = id), show.legend = FALSE)

3.6 Plot trajectories for a few subjects

id.selected <- levels(bmi100$id)[seq(1, nlevels(bmi100$id), length.out = 12)]
bmi100.selected <- subset(bmi100, id %in% id.selected)
subtraj.selected <- subset(subtraj, id %in% id.selected)
ggplot(data = subtraj.selected, mapping = aes(age, bmi)) + 
  geom_line(data = subtraj.selected, mapping = aes(color = id), show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(facets = vars(id)) +
  geom_point(data = bmi100.selected, mapping = aes(color = id), show.legend = FALSE)

3.7 Predict and plot population trajectory

poptraj.sexF <- data.frame(age = age.grid, lage = log(age.grid),
                           sex = sex.grid[1])
spl.term.sexF <- get_by_smooth(fit$gam, "s(lage)", "F")
spl.value.sexF <- eval_smooth(spl.term.sexF, model = fit$gam, data = poptraj.sexF)$data[[1]]$est
poptraj.sexF$bmi <- spl.value + fit$gam$coefficients[["(Intercept)"]]

poptraj.sexM <- data.frame(age = age.grid, lage = log(age.grid),
                           sex = sex.grid[2])
spl.term.sexM <- get_by_smooth(fit$gam, "s(lage)", "M")
spl.value.sexM <- eval_smooth(spl.term.sexM, model = fit$gam, data = poptraj.sexM)$data[[1]]$est
poptraj.sexM$bmi <- spl.value + fit$gam$coefficients[["(Intercept)"]] + fit$gam$coefficients[["sexM"]]

poptraj <- rbind(poptraj.sexF, poptraj.sexM)

ggplot(data = poptraj, mapping = aes(age, bmi)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = sex))

4 Exercises

  1. Try bmi ~ s(lage, id, bs = "fs", xt = "ps", k = 10, m = c(2, 2)).

  2. Try bmi ~ s(lage, bs = 'ps', k = 10, m = c(2, 2)) + s(lage, id, bs = "fs", xt = "ps", k = 10, m = c(2, 2)).
